keep.name: Trailer Park
keep.description: Trailer Park is one of those places that has a photobooth because it has to, the kind of place that would feel empty without one. It's a palace of kitsch, coming in all forms: retro this, Elvis that, tiki and bowling and Pat Boone LPs and everything else you might expect. Unfortunately, the booth was out of order when I visited. Thanks to Christine for the tip. UPDATE 5/22/14: We've received many tips over the years that the booth at the Trailer Park is still not working, and we figured ten years is a good window. So, ten years after my visit, Liz P. confirms that yes, it's still broken, and is "unofficially used as a storage closet." Contributed by Brian, Liz P.

keep.name: The Fat Black Pussycat
keep.description: This bar and lounge located in the West Village was pretty empty when I visited on a Saturday afternoon, but I can imagine it getting pretty crowded by nighttime. The bartender kindly let me into the lounge area, filled with couches, pillows, and rugs, where I found the photobooth at the top of the stairs. The machine took my money and took my photos, but the strip never came out into the drying slot. The bartender called his boss to see if there was anything to be done, but no one was around to give us a hand. He returned my money, and I had to make do with a discarded strip I found when I ran my hand along the top of the booth - thanks for the tip on that technique, Steve. And if that's you in the photo, I'm happy to send it back to you, just drop us a line. UPDATE: As of October 20, 2007, this photobooth is no longer located at the Fat Black Pussycat. Thanks to Tahlia for the tip.

keep.name: Schubas
keep.description: This nice rounded-end Model 14 black and white photobooth sits (where else?) next to the Golden Tee game at the end of the bar before the entrance to the performance space of this well-known music venue. Schubas itself, a 1903 building built by the Schlitz Brewing Co., is a restored treasure with full bar, restaurant, and music hall. The evening I stopped by, the photos from Schubas' booth came out with the back fairly coated in dirty residue and the front somewhat flecked with dirt as well. An uneven edge on each photo was also visible, as well as a light streak down all four photos, but otherwise, the contrast and tonal range of the photos was terrific. UPDATE 3/2/12: Taylor Anne used the booth and reported the booth was working fine. UPDATE 7/6/13: Nikki writes that the booth is in fine working order. UPDATE 11/6/16: Andrew writes with the sad news that the Schuba's booth has been replaced by a digital machine. Contributed by Brian, Taylor Anne, Nikki, Andrew Kropp.

keep.name: Quimby's Bookstore
keep.description: Quimby's is an independently owned bookstore that specializes in independently published and small press books, comics, and zines. The booth, a Model 21, is located in the northeast corner of the store, near the art and film zines. Using the burgundy curtain instead of the light blue curtain for your background allows a nicer contrast. Famed author and radio commentator Dishwasher Pete is featured in the sample photo. UPDATE 3/1/12: Taylor Anne visited and reported the booth was 'broken and not operating; store did not know when it would be fixed.' UPDATE 12/26/12: Betsy reports 'I visited on 12/26/12 with my boyfriend and the booth worked great. The person working behind the counter had no problem with us just using the booth and not buying anything.' UPDATE 11/9/16: The booth is still going strong as of a visit today, according to Andrew. UPDATE 12/27/20: Thanks to Parker for the update: 'The booth is still up and running in good shape! The borders are white and the images are clear with sepia toning. It costs $4 and produces 4 images on a sheet. They unplug the machine 15 mins before closing.' UPDATE 10/2/23: Corinne reports that 'Quimby's no longer has a photobooth. A sign at the front of the store directs visitors to other photobooth locations around the city.' Contributed by Liz, Taylor Anne, Betsy, Andrew Kropp, Parker, Corinne.

keep.name: Reckless Records
keep.description: This Auto-Photo Studio Model 21GB is a new addition to the Wicker Park scene. As Darcy writes, "While the booth did seem safe, there was an odd phantom light at the top of each frame. Whether or not these kinds of glitches are innate defects or if I cause them with all the shaking I do, I will never know." **UPDATE** 2/29/12: Taylor Anne visited and noted "booth broken and not operating; store did not know when it would be fixed." **UPDATE** 4/14/12: Shannon visited and reported the booth was working, but with some chemical issues. **UPDATE** 10/21/15: Mark reports that Reckless Records "moved down the street and did not bring their photobooth along with them :(." Contributed by Darcy, Taylor Anne, Shannon, Mark.
